00:41.442 --> 01:08.867
lines of my training although the first time 
around or the first one and a half times around I

00:41.442 --> 01:08.867
think it was still three quarters or so biology of 
marine organisms but Since then, it was

01:09.151 --> 01:28.577
biological oceanography proper, with strong 
emphasis on production biology, very little on

01:09.151 --> 01:28.577
zoogeography, or biogeography, which I consider 
to be another legitimate part of biological

01:09.151 --> 01:28.577
oceanography, but I didn't know much about it, so 
it was primarily production biology. And I

01:30.211 --> 01:41.287
lectured to biologists and non-biologists, that 
is, biological oceanographers and

01:30.211 --> 01:41.287
non-biological oceanographers, who in those 
years all were sitting through the same courses.

01:41.407 --> 01:51.883
And these upper division lectures were 
prescribed in our undergraduate curriculum, but

01:41.407 --> 01:51.883
all graduate students who came from the outside 
had to take them, too. So it was a very mixed

01:52.063 --> 01:54.987
audience. The biologists in those years often 
accused me of that I really did not address them,

01:55.760 --> 02:23.404
but I was addressing the other ones, the 
non-biologists, because I treated life in the

01:55.760 --> 02:23.404
ocean, which they had come to study, I treated life 
in the ocean strictly in terms of carbon or

01:55.760 --> 02:23.404
chlorophyll and so on, which is very easy then for 
physical and say chemical oceanographers to

01:55.760 --> 02:23.404
understand, but not very not firing up the 
imagination of the biologists but this emphasis

02:24.008 --> 02:47.333
was not really to please the non-biologists or to 
make it easy for them but it was really my way of

02:24.008 --> 02:47.333
outlook that I thought that in terms of 
chlorophyll you can compare the North Pacific

02:24.008 --> 02:47.333
with the North Atlantic or the North Pacific in the 
temperate North Pacific with the tropical North

02:47.920 --> 02:51.972
Pacific. Whereas if you had species lists, well, 
you couldn't really. So it was designed. But many

02:57.789 --> 03:00.256
bollushes were very unhappy and still are. But 
that is just my way of looking at the world. At that

03:04.559 --> 03:09.143
time, I thought already of writing it up, writing a 
textbook. The lecture notes, at least, were

03:09.464 --> 03:20.194
organized such that they were proper referencing 
where did I get this idea from and where did that

03:09.464 --> 03:20.194
slide come from, because there was no book which 
treated the ocean. There was no book on biological

03:20.214 --> 03:22.055
oceanography. The oceans were way outdated 
already then. I think they were outdated when they

03:24.978 --> 03:28.101
were written, as far as biology is concerned. 
Otherwise, a very good book, but in biology, quite

03:28.241 --> 03:32.305
so so. Well, I will come back to that book later. I 
didn't get to it yet.

03:38.740 --> 03:50.749
I did draw early on the results of model studies, of 
theoretical studies in biological

03:38.740 --> 03:50.749
oceanography, which also was done rarely in those 
years. But because I was not trained

03:51.202 --> 04:01.054
mathematically enough, I could not really teach 
by means of models, which would be the most elegant

03:51.202 --> 04:01.054
way. Nobody did it in those years except Reilly 
himself. But at least I used the results and said,

04:04.058 --> 04:11.447
look, students, that is the future. And again, 
until very recently, until Parsons' textbook

04:13.690 --> 04:20.719
came about, there was no text on which you could 
draw.

04:25.508 --> 04:31.296
As far as research is concerned, I emphasize 
plankton methods. I continue to be interested in

04:31.376 --> 04:37.544
methods, and especially of the assessment of 
phytoplankton standing stock. That is the

04:38.145 --> 04:40.669
inheritance from cry. I was a little disenchanted 
with the chemical method, but I also did not want to

04:42.111 --> 04:47.618
have phytoplankton theses and phytoplankton 
written which just had long species lists. So in

04:52.843 --> 05:01.573
the first years, very much on my mind was the 
problem of how to convert from species lists into

04:52.843 --> 05:01.573
mass estimates. And the theses by Lawrence, for 
example, and by Hobson, the master theses by both,

05:01.593 --> 05:12.525
and also by Strathman were very much concerned 
with those issues. In a way, I did not continue with

05:15.104 --> 05:34.699
zooplankton work, and the reason is that in 1961, 
there was a symposium held in Copenhagen on

05:15.104 --> 05:34.699
zooplankton, which was to be the successor to that 
mentioned 1957 symposium on primal production.

05:35.810 --> 05:40.919
The zooplankton symposium was not nearly as good 
as the phytoplankton symposium, but that's

05:35.810 --> 05:40.919
besides the point. I was invited, no, I think I 
contributed a paper on the role of the small

05:41.760 --> 05:54.582
zooplankton, which nobody on this continent at 
that time talked about, which is again bringing

05:41.760 --> 05:54.582
up, reminding the people of the Lohmann idea. I 
just reviewed literature and said, now look,

05:54.602 --> 06:01.193
there are many, many organisms which slip through 
the meshes you use. and I was invited to give a

06:02.489 --> 06:14.507
review on the vertical distribution of 
soroplankton, which I did, but that was not well

06:02.489 --> 06:14.507
done in my opinion, so I rewrote it and re-expanded 
it and finished that in 1963 and that was published

06:15.517 --> 06:21.626
in 1964. And in that review, of course I reviewed 
among other things the vertical migration issue,

06:22.547 --> 06:33.102
pointing out that very often organisms don't 
migrate, which I had mentioned before. But I also

06:34.263 --> 06:44.798
elaborated on, or I touched upon, the problem of 
the vertical distribution of very small

06:34.263 --> 06:44.798
zooplankton, say CLJs and nauplii, in the mixed 
layer. and When I finished that review, I thought

06:47.208 --> 07:09.618
the only really interesting aspect in 
zooplankton work, besides biogeography, which

06:47.208 --> 07:09.618
is a different issue, but otherwise the only 
really important issue before us is this question

06:47.208 --> 07:09.618
of the zooplankton as a mixed layer, which ties 
into production studies, and I can't go into this.

07:10.739 --> 07:16.827
The upshot as far as my own scientific future is 
concerned was that I realized that I couldn't do it

07:10.739 --> 07:16.827
myself. First, it involved revisiting of 
populations, which is objectively difficult to

07:17.262 --> 07:26.625
come back to the same population in the open sea. It 
can't be done even now. But the other issue is of the

07:29.051 --> 07:33.482
statistical problems. to which I can't go into 
either, but at any rate I realized that I didn't

07:34.137 --> 07:48.970
have the equipment, training-wise, nor the 
logistics behind me, and so I just left it at that,

07:34.137 --> 07:48.970
and it is only beginning to be picked up now. Well, 
people begin to think about along these lines now.

07:53.995 --> 08:02.743
But I was so discouraged that I just left 
zooplankton work, distribution work, and have

07:53.995 --> 08:02.743
never done it ever since, although, of course, I 
still lecture about it.

08:05.693 --> 08:12.202
the, what shall I say, I was to say major 
accomplishment, but that is a little too much.

